description.text:
Customize-able lattice cube.

Original concept by the prolific Angus Deveson, Maker's Muse

Play with the beam diameter parameter to stress harder :) Other parameters alter the quantity and size of the cubes, and the number of repeated lattices.

I've provided three .STLs here, with strut diameter 2.4mm, 2.0mm, and 1.6mm.

Clearly the weakest part of the structure and print is the initial beams going out from the base, as these float in free space including their first branches, before being attached back to the main structure. Beyond that point it's quite stable regardless, until it gets towards the top and the layer size drops below the minimum cooling time.

Update - added parameter for number of lattices to repeat.

Update - added a monster lattice STL. I don't have a successful print to share from the FDM, but the resin printer had no problem with it!

Also, just for the fun of it - added a photo of a resin print of a 12-fold repeated lattice which yields a neat sort of rotunda thing.

Relevant mods to my i3 plus are a decent cooler (the DiiiCooler by Pawpawpaw85), and the Micro-Swiss all-metal hot end (with which I'm using a 0.25mm retraction distance for my PLA).

description.text:
My simple vat cover, both lid and base.

This cover is boring flat on the top to make it easy to print, but has a lip around the edge to match the vat, creating a reliable enough seal for storage. It also has a strengthening grid on the underside, for no particularly good reason.

The base is even more simple, idea being to protect the FEP from accidental damage when the vat is stored.

The third .stl is the base with a big hole cut out the middle - I did this to check print dimensions before printing the main two pieces to avoid waste during development; it may also be useful to check before printing that your dimension calibration matches mine - and if not, to calculate a scaling factor for printing the lid itself.

title: Exakta lenses to Pentax Q adapter with IHAGEE M40 macro tube

description.text:
Just got this #135 Sun Telephoto 135mm f3.8 a nice 1950s lens with exakta mount. Paid all $4.99 in thrift store for it together with IHAGEE macro tubes so I was anxious to try it. It seems the Pentax Q would be the best candidate.
The flange focus distance of those Exakta lenses is 44.7mm but Pentax Q Flange distance is about 10mm so my lens needs a tube about 35mm from the Q in order to focus. Now I could print a 35mm tube with Q bayonet and model exakta mount on the other end , but because those lenses are heavy, this would likely result in mechanical failure in the EXA complicated bayonet. A better way is to reuse one of those IHAGEE macro tubes - these macro tubes are plentiful and cheap because it is very little you can do with them now - but they are multi sectional with M40x0.75 thread between sections so it is easy to get the correct size.
So I decided to do a smaller adapter with Q bayonet on one side and internal M40x0.75 on the other side to accommodate the few sections of IHAGEE tubes that have exakta mount at the end.

I am very pleased with the result!

description.text:
A Dugout for the Dynavap with a slide top and extra space for a quad torch/lighter/whatever else.
I love the Dynastash, but not the twisty top which came loose over time for me. This dugout is designed so that a magnet on the top is optional, but I do recommend them as the slide will come loose as well over time.

This is currently made to hold the Stinger Quad Torch Lighter by Vertigo which is available over at Dynavap's website: https://www.dynavap.com/dynashop/accessories/quad-torch-lighter

The lighter's dimensions from the site show: 8.2cm x 3.5cm x 1.9cm

To fit, I measured with some calipers and made the lighter hole this size:

X,Y,Z (X)40mm x (Y)20mm x (Z)88mm

***Important, if you want your Dynavap to center in the magnet like the OG Dynastash, you will need to purchase a DIAMETRICALLY aligned magnet for the middle. If you do not specifically look for this you might end up with a magnet that is AXIALLY aligned by mistake and the Dynavap will not stick in the middle of your disc magnet. Trust me, I know this, I made this mistake.

***You can also just order the magnet provided by Dynavap in their website, but as I designed this with a thicker magnet disc, the one from Dynavap will look pushed in, I might design another case so that it looks almost flush and works with the magnet from Dynavap.

title: Original Prusa i3 MK2/MK2S/MMU pinda probe cooler

description.text:
The PINDA probe on the original PRUSA i3 MK2/S has an achilles heel: when it heats up, it detects the bed too early. (This will be remedied by the soon to be released PINDA 2 which actively compensates for the temperature of the probe).

This is particularly a problem when printing materials requiring a high bed temperature in an enclosure, especially if a print is aborted and restarted soon afterward.

This cooler helps with this issue by blowing unheated air from outside the enclosure over the PINDA during the bed heating cycle.

MATERIALS REQUIRED:
1x EK1713 Limit Switch

1x 50X15mm centrifugal fan This can be either 5v or 12v, depending on how you plan to power it.

2-3 feet of 9/16" OD Vinyl tubing Commonly sold by the foot at most hardware stores

Wire
Power supply for fan
M3X10mm machine screws (x8)

Wiring

Because the cooler is triggered mechanically, there are many options for powering the fan. The simplest is to repurpose a suitable AC to DC wall transformer.

Wire the limit switch as follows

  1. Positive lead of power supply -> Common terminal of limit switch (C)
  2. Normally open terminal of limit switch (NO) -> Fan positive terminal
  3. Fan negative terminal -> Negative lead of power supply.

ADVANCED OPTION: It is also possible to power the cooler using the Mini-rambo's outputs. I will not describe this process in detail since you could damage your printer if you don't know what you are doing.

On the V1.3 mini rambo, A 5V blower fan can be powered by pin 2 and pin 4 of the P3 expansion header

A 12 volt blower can be powered from the mini rambo by multiplexing the part cooling fan output. Use the NC and C terminals of the limit switch to direct power to the part fan when the limit switch is open, and the NO and C terminals of the limit switch to divert power to the pinda cooler when the limit switch is closed. You would also need to alter the startup gcode to activate and shutdown the part fan for this setup to work. (M106 S255 ; turn on part fan M106 S0; turn off part fan.)

Assembly

Press the limit switch and wiring into the cooler nozzle. The free end of the limit switch arm must face away from the heatbed.

Place the cooler nozzle on top of the right Z axis stepper motor. Slide the bottom bracket under the motor, taking care not to pinch the stepper motor's wiring. Secure the nozzle to the bottom bracket using 4 * M3X10mm machine screws.

Insert the blower motor into the fan holder body, taking care to route the fan wires through the smaller hole. Secure the fan cover to the fan body with 4 * M3X10mm machine screws.

9/16" OD vinyl tubing serves as an air duct between the blower and nozzle. The blower must be mounted outside the enclosure.

Slic3r startup gcode to activate cooler

Startup gcode is used to activate the cooling fan by moving the tip of the pinda probe to the X and Z coordinates where it activates the limit switch.
IMPORTANT Some calibration of the exact X and Z position may be necessary. You may need to change the values in bold below to ensure that everything activates properly. May not be compatible with all fan shroud designs

;EXAMPLE STARTUP GCODE
M115 U3.0.12 ; tell printer latest fw version
; Start G-Code sequence START
T[initial_tool];
M140 S[first_layer_bed_temperature];
G21 ; set units to millimeters
G90 ; use absolute coordinates
M83 ; use relative distances for extrusion

;START OF PINDA COOLER GCODE
G28 X Y Z; Home X Y and Z axes
G90; Switch to absolute coordinates
G1 Z5 F2000; Raise nozzle to 5mm above bed
G1 X230 F8000; Rapid move to end of x carriage;
G1 X247.5 F600; Slowly move to limit switch
M190 S[first_layer_bed_temperature];
M104 S[first_layer_temperature];
G4 P60000; dwell for 30 seconds (gives extruder time to heat)
G1 X220 F600; back off to turn off fan
;END PINDA COOLING SEQUENCE

G28 W ; Mesh bed levelling routine with a cool pinda
G80
G92 E0.0
M203 E100
M92 E140 ;(change if setting a custom esteps/mm value)
M109 S[first_layer_temperature]; If extruder not at temp yet, wait for it.
G1 Z0.250 F7200.000
G1 X50.0 E80.0 F1000.0
G1 X160.0 E20.0 F1000.0
G1 Z0.200 F7200.000
G1 X220.0 E13 F1000.0
G1 X240.0 E0 F1000.0
G1 E-4 F1000.0
G92 E0.0

This is only for people who print with PLA and turn off the heated bed entirely. Like me :)

Glass would be best, but I was impatient so I cut a piece of 1/4" plexi to 6x12.5 inches. I just clipped it to my existing build plate. When my glass arrives, I will replace the existing build plate with the glass. For now, this works just fine. The platform will need to be slightly off center (to the left).
The only change yoou need to make to your machine is to move the Z axis end stop. Just take it off and put it in the adjustable slots and set it inbetween the two laser cut set of holes. Picture attached. 
Lastly, just adjust the center of your build platform in ReplicatorG -> "Onboard Preferences". My numbers for that are: X home offest = 163 Y home offest = 75.

This is a remix of rwindr's original cartridge holder for the Nintendo Switch. Changes include:

  • Made a parameterized model in OpenSCAD based on rwindr's original design.
  • Added the ability to specify the number of cartridges in the X and Y axis and also to customize many aspects of the print (window size, base thickness etc).
  • Increased the default size of the window to accommodate those of us with stubby little fingers.
  • Re-designed the nubs that hold the cartridge in-place...not sure if I did a better or worse job than the original or how it will hold up in the long-term, so all feedback appreciated.

The tolerances are a little tight on this, you may want to print a 1x1 first to make sure it's still a good fit with your own printer and then either edit the SCAD file or scale the print accordingly.

Apologies to antwr for posting this so soon after his original upload...I really liked his design and with the holiday season approaching wanted one that would accommodate more cartridges.

title: Parametric Phone Case Design for All Brands

description.text:
Knowing that Fusion 360 software has the feature of parametric design, I decided to try it out on a phone case. It is a design for all brands of mobile phones. The phone case has one button opening on both the left and right side and a camera opening on the front.

You may simply enter the parameters such as width, height, position and width of the buttons and camera openings and you are ready to go. The software will generate a phone case of your own!

The attached stl file is a Samsung S6 case made with this parametric design. I have tested the .f3D file with different phone models. So far it works pretty well.

Here are the steps:

Step 1 :

Click the link below to access the design file or you can download the .f3D file here. Of course you need to have the Fusion 360 software (and a bit knowledge about the software) in order to work with the file.

http://a360.co/2iGjN72

Step 2 :

Open the file , select Modify and Change Parameters. Enter the values with reference to your phone size. The values listed below are for the making of Samsung S6 case. Vaules are in minimetres.

Width = 67 (width of the base plate of the phone case )
Height = 140 (height of the base plate of the phone case )
RoundCornerRadius = 4 (round corner radius of the base plate )
ArcWidth = 2 (side bulge/curve of the case )
ArcHeight = 7 (height of the side bulge)
LeftButton1Postion(camera facing up) = 45 (measuring from the top of the base plate)
LeftButton1Width = 15 (width of the button opening )
RightButton1Position = 15 (measuring from the top of the base plate)
RightButton1Width = 30 (width of the button opening)
CameraPostionX = 25 (measuring from the left of the base plate)
CameraPositionY = 15 (measuring from the top of the base plate)
Camera Width = 28 (width of the camera opening)
Camera Height = 15 (height of the camera opening)

Notes :

(A)Please take good care of the position and the dimension of the button openings and the overall size of the phone case. Entering the wrong numbers may cause errors and generate no output. I suggest to make a draft on papers before changing the values.

(B) Please aware the Width and Height are not the actual size of your phone but the size of the base plate of the phone case. You may determine the Width and Height with reference to the following equation.

Width + ArcWidth x 2 = width of the phone + clearance

(C) The thickness of the phone case is fixed at 2mm by default and cannot be changed. The height of the button openings is fixed by default and is equal to the ArcHeight value you enter.

Step 3 :

Try different values and see how it goes before actually print out the phone case . Enjoy!

At last, I have attached a 2D drawing (Fusion 360 really did a great job) with reference to above parameters for the design of a Samsung S6 phone case. I hope that it helps you to understand my design and revise the parameters to make your own.

The answer is really up to you and your skills at flying stuff. Juste remember that the stiffer you build this frame, the weaker your plane & motor will be (but frame will be durable, blah blah blah). Or make it intentionnally weak, and vibrations / shocks / crashes will destroy it in a finger snap.

Stiff configuration :: fill it with more than 50 %
weak :: Basically try to fill it the less you can (thin walls, very large filling cavities).

Note : You'll need to print 2 "Top Plate" which will be used as top and bottom plates for this project.

Assembly

Simply connect all parts with screws (or glue if you don't have fitting plastic screws).
Nothing more is required , simply make sure the motor's wires are safely put out of the moving parts' way.

Very early prototype version. Notice how wires go outside before going back inside the frame. Plug your ESC using the back plate's central hole.

I am sick of having my FPV quad motors bend and bearings rattling after a day of garage racing. The motor protectors that are currently out there only protect the bell, the part that hardly ever hits something.

The broken motors are mainly caused by impacts between the hard motor axle and the hard concrete you are crashing on. both those things don't flex at all resulting in bend axle or rattling bearings. These little motor bouncers give the top of the motor about 3mm for deaccelerating the impact of a crash.

Drawbacks are that you need some extras because you lose them easily. Also your motor gets about a gram more heavy with the bouncer on there.

*for best result print in TPU with 25% infill for extra bouncyness

I'm not very good with CAD and i hope to see many improvements of my design, please give credit, that's all i want.

The project is still under construction, the cable car's are not going very smooth on the pole's. If someone has an idea to solve this problem, let me now. If you have other comment's ore problems let me also now, i will try to help where i can.

Extra material.:
You need 12 bearings from the type 623zz. These are used in the pole's and pully's.
As a motor i used the small dc motor from amazon. You can feed this with 2 small AAA batteries in a holder. The cable for the motor you can feed thru a spare box in the under station. If you not glue the roof on you can power on by just stick in the batteries.
You can find the motor in this link
http://www.amazon.com/30RPM-Torque-Geared-Gearbox-Electric/dp/B00GYRSDSE/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1421622485&sr=8-
M3 set screws and M3 hexagonal bolts. with some nuts to screw.

Under station.:
You just print every part an fit it with the bearings, motor and pully's. I used some rubber band's to connect the 2 puly's. If you not glue the roof, u can use the battery box on the side of the house.

Cabine.:
Print the cabine, handle bars, bumpers, arm and hook. The best whey to rint the handle bars is with the bur op. You printer need to print a very small surface but with mine is works good. Than you glue the parts to the cabine. The hook and arm you connect whit a piece of 1.75 mm filament. At the ends you meld it a little so that the hinge don't fell out. Now the cabine can rotate free from the hook. In the hook you need to put a m3 set screw. After that you can feed the wire thru the gap and fix the wire with the m3 screw. You can connect also the 2 ends of the wire like this.
The hook printing is verry hard to do. It is so small that s3D things it is in inch and give you a message. Just ignore the message and try to find a good position to print it.

upper station.:
The station fits more or less the same as the under station, only on this one i put a clamp on the base. Mine is clamped on the wood box around my window, but i think that every wood from less than 18mm will possible to clamp on.

Also, as a wind generator, it can provide autonomous power to remote electronic devices (for example, video cameras and Wi-Fi access points, LoRa systems and much more).

All the modeling is done in Fusion 360 and partially in Autodesk 123D Design.

The Bonka is a result of a 2.5 week long course called "Digital Fabrication".
My goal was it to create a piggy bank, which is neither childish nor for adults only. A simple and calm object, which is decorative and makes fun to save money. It was important to me that the piggy bank is resealable, stable and easy to manage. The result works with an elastic band, which connects the nose and the bottom through the can. The part with the ears has exactly the diameter of a usual can what guarantees that it doesn't fall away.

The Bonka is produced with a CNC-machine. You take the .dxf file, define the depths and shape it. Afterwards you clean and cut smooth the parts.
Nearly finished!
Now you get yourself a can, open both sides, use an elastic band to keep the nose and bottom together, make a knot at the end (what is the pig's tail) and you are finished.
Enjoy saving your money!

description.text:
Tokens and holder for tracking your spell slots. Prints without support. The base tray had 1st, 2nd and 3rd level spell slots and a small holder. The "Base Slider" is the cover for the storage space. You can print the base tray and later add the other "tray" models as your character advances, they should just pop in.

The large base has all 9 spell levels.

If you are printing the numbers with a second filament color, stop the first color at 1mm for the tokens and 10mm for the bases. The slider should be printed at 0.1mm layer height, and the base above 7.9mm should also, so that the slider fits properly. Should print without supports.

Edit: I added revised versions of the 4 through 7 trays that have their own little storage area.

Edit2: Shrank the tokens down by 0.2mm so they fit 4 tokens deep better.

comments.text: Great idea! I've started printing this and I love it. A couple points of feedback, The small side of the slide clip seems thin. I had to reinforce mine, maybe this was a printing issue but I feel if they were a little thicker this wouldn't be such a problem. Also there doesn't quite seem to be enough storage for tokens. Or I've done something horribly wrong... my print of level 1-3 I stack 3 tokens per tray. Based on that your full-size tray is short 8 tokens worth of storage and the mini set finally has enough token storage by level 6. This means however that until I'm an 11th level Wizard I have to snap 1 extra row of spell levels on to make room to store my extra token. I know I'm being really picky about the modular one but the full-size has it the worst it flat out can't store all my tokens and be tossed in my bag. I'm going to try and remix it but I'm not very experienced in 3D modeling I'll share any improvements if I'm successful.
comments.author: daveleblanc

comments.text: Haven't had a problem with the slider.  What layer height are you printing at?  It's really designed for the slider (and at least the slot on the base) to be printed at 0.1mm.
